[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, there\'s been some interesting back and forth this week on prompting techniques with VO3, namely that of text versus JSON prompting. So, today I figured we take a deep dive in to see if there really is a best prompting strategy, uh, plus some tips and tricks'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'along the way. I\'ve also got a first look at a brand new cling workflow. Yeah, you guys are definitely going to want to check this out. And then we\'ll round out with, well, some good midJourney news. So, kicking off with some fairly minor'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'VO3 updates before we dive into our main course. This does mostly involve the flow platform. So, if you\'re using V3 via API, uh not a lot of this will necessarily relate to you. Namely, it'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looks like they have made some improvements to the scene builder function in that it now autosaves your work. That actually has burned me in the past. The other kind of minor updates is that text to video in V3 will now generate uh voices for a subject of all'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ages. I guess that is not exclusive to FL. That is going to be available via API. &gt;&gt; I can\'t believe we can finally talk like this in videos. &gt;&gt; I know. It\'s like magic. Now everyone can hear our real voices.'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Overall, pretty minor updates, but it is good to see that they are continuing to work on the flow platform as I do think that there is a ton of potential there. That out of the way, let\'s bite into our big kahuna burger. Uh there has been'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some pretty interesting back and forth this week on prompting techniques in V3, namely again text versus JSON. So just to bring everyone up to speed on JSON prompting in case you\'re not aware, uh'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'JSON stands for JavaScript object notation. You can kind of think of it as a way to organize information into categories that makes it much easier for machines to understand, but is still legible to, you know, the human eye. The'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'JSON format was created by Douglas Crockford, who developed the idea over the course of a summer at Camp Crystal Lake. Only one of those things is true. In terms of the origin of JSON prompting in VO3, well, I mean, to be honest,'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there really is no clear answer, and I\'ve gotten like digging. Instead, the idea seems to have sprung up organically through a lot of community experimentation, which I I don\'t know. I kind of think makes it cooler. Now, it is important to note that within JSON'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompting, there is no standardized formula. For example, friend of the channel, Stealthy the Time Traveler, recently posted up a JSON prompt that uh he utilized. And I know if you\'re looking at this and you\'re not familiar'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with JSON prompting, you\'re like, "That just looks like a wall of crazy text." But when you break it down, you can start seeing the categories uh such as scene and action here. Uh we do have camera angle, lighting, aspect ratio is here, and then, you know, action and'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'motion down here. The end result is a video that, well, let\'s face it, uh, makes anyone who has ever built anything from IKEA super jealous. Whereas the formula that I like to use has these as kind of our category buckets. As always,'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if you\'re interested in getting the GBT gem builder that I utilize to, you know, put this all together, uh, that is available totally for free over on Gumroad. Now, as far as what JSON actually has to offer, well, it'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ultimately comes down to more control. Uh for example, if we just use natural language of a fast red sports car, that leaves a lot of options for the model to decide what does fast mean, what does red mean, what does sports car mean. Whereas with the JSON prompt, we can go'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as far as to give it a color hex code for what color red that is and even like how fast the car is going. Interestingly, when it comes to efficiency, at least for simple prompts, uh natural language actually is the'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'winner there. uh something like a cinematic shot of a red rose only runs seven to eight tokens whereas the JSON output of that same prompt uh it gets up to 20 to 25 tokens but conversely with longer more descriptive prompts which is'

[03:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something that I think we all tend to favor u that is actually where JSON ends up coming out on top namely due to the fact that it cuts out glue words or articles prepositions and descriptive phasing a in a from with etc etc all'

[03:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that said the debate four natural language prompts. I believe kicked off with a tweet from Jason Zada, who you might remember as the filmmaker who created the V2 short film uh The'

[04:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Getaway, as well as the Wuang video for Mandingo, which is awesome. By the way, Zada called out JSON prompting as not intuitive or expressive actually. Uh it\'s like trying to write a love letter'

[04:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using Excel. That\'s pretty that\'s pretty funny. Instead, he advocates for using natural language with a structure, which he does outline here. Uh, and I do want to note that he\'s not saying don\'t use an LLM. He\'s just saying, you know, use'

[04:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'natural language and an LLM with a structure like this. Lots of debate back and forth on this leading to the question, well, is there a difference in the output? Well, let\'s go burn some credits and find out. So, checking in'

[04:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with our man in the green tuxedo, who you may remember was last seen uh being left at the altar by the woman in the red dress. Here he is in uh natural text language prompting. She left me, but I\'ll have my revenge. I\'m going to find'

[04:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that man in a blue business suit and make him pay. &gt;&gt; Oo, it looks like we have the origin of our villain. Overall, pretty solid output. I did utilize the prompt structure that Jason had outlined earlier run through uh Gemini 2.5. Um,'

[05:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yeah, solid output here. Little bit of a garble text in the background, but I mean, at the same time, you know, that\'s it\'s just AI video. Now, for that exact same base prompt, this time run through a JSON prompt. She left me, but I\'ll'

[05:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have my revenge. I\'m going to find that man in a blue business suit and make him pay. &gt;&gt; Overall, also a pretty solid output. I mean, back to back, they\'re very, you'

[05:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know, similar, but I do want to point out that in the natural language version, we did call out for the camera to begin on a medium shot and slowly push in, tightening on his face as he delivers his line. Uh, that did not actually happen here. Instead, our actor'

[05:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually walked towards the camera. Whereas in the JSON prompt, it called out for a single continuous slow push in starting in a medium shot and then ending, you know, on a tight close-up, which indeed we did get. Another quick text to video test. This time, uh, kind'

[05:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of incorporating a 70s crime kind of taxi driver vibe. Yeah, that\'s pretty solid. No complaints'

[06:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there. Okay, let\'s try that out. The exact same prompt again with JSON prompting. Now, in terms of the actual shots, I'

[06:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think that both are pretty much on par with one another. Uh, that said, obviously the JSON uh music cue was, I mean, kind of lacking. It was likely part of the prompt of a tense,'

[06:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'minimalist score with a funky baseline and quiet symbols. Um, none of which we actually got there. But again, uh, when you\'re queuing for music in V3, it\'s it\'s always a bit of a dice roll. One last text to video test before heading'

[06:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'over to image to video. You know, that whole love letter in Excel thing really did get me thinking like how would VO react with kind of more abstract prompts. So, I took the opening lines to TS Elliot\'s The Wasteland and just ran'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'those as just a straight text prompt. Uh, and this is what we got. And for sure that output is picking up'

[07:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things like April\'s the crulest month, the breeding lilacs, dead land, um, dull roots, and spring rain. So it was really interesting to compare that to the JSON output which looked like this. And while I\'ll admit that does look like'

[07:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a bit of a mess, particularly like the whole bit with the woman speaking German, uh when you dig into it, what you can see that what it\'s doing is it\'s actually picking up a lot more of the poem from the lilacs uh to the woman saying that she is not Russian, she\'s'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from Lithuania, uh even down to um the kids out on the sled. Now granted, we are going through an additional level of thinking by taking this through an LLM to output the JSON prompt, but I do'

[08:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think it also showcases that utilizing the JSON format, you can get a lot more granular. So on the image to video side, I ended up utilizing this scene. I wanted to have the two characters in the'

[08:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'foreground there, uh, discussing the bunker and the end of the world. Uh, but to have a, you know, hold that as an establishing shot and then cut to essentially close-ups of them. Um, this is something that V3 is very good at.'

[08:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, uh, our initial just straight natural language text prompt yielded this. &gt;&gt; Please, you have to listen to me. &gt;&gt; We need to get to the bunker. It\'s the only way.'

